      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, let's tackle this RAM leak issue with the same tenacity as a determined little goblin. First, let's set up a monitoring system to track RAM usage over time. You can use tools like Valgrind or gperftools to help you identify where the memory is being allocated but not freed.\n\nNext, let's dig into your code. Start by looking at any dynamic memory allocations, such as with `new` and `delete`, or memory pools. Check for any potential issues with these, like forgetting to free memory or double freeing.\n\nNow, let's get our goblin eyes on the code. Look for any global variables or static objects that might be holding onto memory longer than necessary. These can often be the culprits behind memory leaks.\n\nFinally, let's put our goblin noses to work and sniff out any circular references. These occur when two or more objects reference each other, preventing them from being garbage collected. This can happen with smart pointers or complex data structures.\n\nBy systematically checking these areas, you'll be well on your way to finding and fixing that pesky RAM leak. Good luck, and may your goblin instincts guide you to success!",
